          "List three precise literary or analytical terms relevant to this extract (e.g. dramatic irony, unreliable narrator, projection, cognitive dissonance).",
          "Choose one term and explain exactly how it applies to Ono's voice in this passage.",
          "Now explain how Ono's use of language — the vocabulary he chooses — unconsciously reveals the very trait he is criticising in Shintaro.",
          "Write a sentence using at least two of your chosen terms together in an analytical claim."
        ]
      },
      open: {
        main: "Ishiguro arms Ono with the language of moral authority while simultaneously undermining it. How does the discipline-specific language of literary criticism illuminate what Ono cannot see about himself?",
        steps: []
      },
      essay: {
        main: "Using precise literary terminology, construct a paragraph arguing that Ono's vocabulary of condemnation is also a vocabulary of self-exposure.",
        steps: ["Topic sentence naming the technique.", "Embedded quotation with analysis of specific word choice.", "Link to the theme of hypocrisy in post-war Japan."]
      }
    },
    shintaro: {
      scaffold: {
        main: "What is the precise literary term for the gap between what Ono intends and what the reader understands when he critiques Shintaro — and why does this terminology matter for your analysis?",
        steps: [
          "Define 'dramatic irony' and 'dramatic monologue' in your own words.",
          "Apply one of these terms to a specific moment in the Shintaro extract.",
          "Explain why naming the technique with precision changes the weight of your argument.",
          "Write one sentence that uses the term correctly embedded within your own syntax."
        ]
      },
      open: {
        main: "The literary critic's vocabulary — irony, unreliable narrator, dramatic monologue — becomes particularly charged when applied to Ono's attack on Shintaro. Select two terms and show how they interact in this passage.",
        steps: []
      },
      essay: {
        main: "Write a TEEL paragraph in which you deploy at least two literary terms to analyse how Ishiguro uses Ono's critique of Shintaro to implicate Ono himself.",
        steps: ["Topic sentence.", "Evidence (embedded quotation).", "Explanation using literary terminology.", "Link to the novel's broader concern with self-deception."]
      }
    },
    setting: {
      scaffold: {
        main: "What literary devices are at work in the Mrs Kawakami bar scene, and how does naming them precisely change the depth of your reading?",
        steps: [
          "Identify the specific device used to present the bar (e.g. pathetic fallacy, juxtaposition, symbolism).",
          "Write a definition of your chosen device.",
          "Apply it to a specific detail in the extract — name the detail and explain the effect.",
          "Use the device's name in a sentence that forms the basis of a topic sentence."
        ]
      },
      open: {
        main: "The language of literary criticism provides a lens for the setting. Use at least two precise terms to argue what the Kawakami bar scene reveals about Ono's relationship to change.",
        steps: []
      },
      essay: {
        main: "Write a paragraph in which you analyse the setting of the bar using precise literary terminology, arguing that the physical space functions as an externalisation of Ono's internal conflict.",
        steps: []
      }
    },
    nostalgia: {
      scaffold: {
        main: "What literary and historical terms most precisely describe Ono's attitude to the past — and how does choosing 'nostalgia' over 'sentimentality' or 'melancholy' shift the analysis?",
        steps: [
          "Distinguish between nostalgia, sentimentality and melancholy as critical terms.",
